<!-- Slide 10: Key takeaways -->
<div class="content-slide takeaway-slide">
  <p class="overline">Back To The Thesis</p>
  <h2>What Coding Agents Change At Work</h2>
  <ol class="takeaway-list">
    <li>
      <strong>They act through code, not just chat.</strong>
      Code lets agents reach files, tools, APIs, docs, tickets, dashboards, and workflows.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Knowledge work becomes a loop.</strong>
      Research, triage, review, analysis, and docs become: gather context, act, inspect, improve.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The harness decides the coworker.</strong>
      Context, tools, routing, permissions, memory, and stopping rules shape whether the agent is useful.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Trust has to be engineered.</strong>
      Sandboxes, tests, rubrics, gates, and review points make delegation safe enough for real work.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Start with one recurring workflow.</strong>
      Pick one everyday task, make the loop measurable, then own the smallest harness you can change.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <div class="closing">
    <p class="closing__text">The point is not automating coding. <strong>It is giving everyday knowledge work a reliable action loop.</strong></p>
  </div>
</div>
